It's a nice song, but she's a mediocre singer in reality! 
Her Brother (sorry that he happens to be a man, could just have likely been her sister, if her sister was a producer *sigh*)
Anyway, her Brother Finneas O'Connell is the genius behind the scenes, who 'doubles' her voice, glosses over it with added 'sheen', eq'ed 'air', and very beautiful subtle reverb and delay.
She's whisper quiet too, so you need to 'gate' and 'de-ess' the shit out of that signal, while tending too or hoping she's controlled enough to avoid lip smacking or deep breaths. 

You don't have to dig far to hear her unprocessed vocal! Those pro's listening, talk about how she sounds like anyone else, if it wasn't for Finneas. 
Live, isn't truly live. She's singing on an audio 'bus' with about 30 different 'returns' on her voice, adding those effects 'live'. 

Put her in a room with you, singing to you face to face and you'd assume she was having an off day. 

Facts are facts people.

text: What Was I Made For? came out at the right time for me. I've struggled with my identity for a couple of years now. I've had a pretty shit year health wise which has given me plenty of time to reflect on how I am feeling and who I am as a person. I'm bi. I am bisexual. That is who I am, without question nor debate and deep down, I knew this however I was too afraid to approach it, acknowledge it and be proud of it. I'm 27 and I have felt a great fear since 25 that I am too old to only just recognize this part of myself and most importantly tell people. This song allowed me to process my emotions, challenge my thoughts and perceptions of how people would react and how I feel in myself. It allowed me to acknowledge that things will be okay. Maybe not right in this moment, but it will. I am who I am and I should not be ashamed of that and as Nick Nelson would say... "I'm bi...actually." :)
